segments.text: Okay, and you were wounded now.
When was this, D plus 1?
I was wounded about 7 o'clock on D plus 1, about a mile out of St. Mary Glees.
And I was actually leading a patrol because we didn't have anybody else to lead it.
And I had 13 soldiers, and this included one sergeant and one lieutenant.
And we had gone about 100 yards when
I felt this bullet pass by and I yelled to the ditch and as I moved toward the ditch I got hit in the left forehead.
Oh, you're lucky.
Yeah, lucky.
I sure was.
And I was put in an aid station by this sergeant that was with me.
And the next day transferred to an aid station in the field out in the open ground.
that afternoon, given a blood transfusion and placed on a hospital ship out in the harbor there about five miles from here.
Do you remember the name of the ship?
No, never did know really.
I was pretty well sedated when they carried me out.
And they carried me back to England and landed in Southampton and took me up to the Midlands place.
I've forgotten now, right out of Market Harbor.
I can't even think of the name of this place.
But anyhow, they had about 25 hospitals in this area.
How long did it take you to get from the point where you were wounded to a regular hospital?
I think five days.
Five days?
I spent a night in their barn down there, the first night, all day and all night.
And they moved me out from the barn early the next morning to this field place where they had all these blood bottles hanging up.
They gave me some transfusion.
Put me in a truck and carried me to the beach, and I was in a beach hospital there for about 12 hours.
And then they put me on one of these landing crafts, carried me out and pulled us up in baskets from the landing craft up the side.
We landed back in England, and they operated on me the next morning.
I had considerable damage done, and I had two young doctors, incidentally.
one from Philadelphia and one from Rochester.
But they made an examination and told me what they thought they had to do, but they had to have my permission first.
So I gave permission and they started operating on me the next morning at 6 o'clock and operated until about 1 that afternoon.
Could you tell me what they had to do?
Yes.
Well, this bone was...
The bullet entered here and barely missed my eye and went in here and came out here.
It was coming this direction.
Just a rifle bullet?
Rifle bullet, sniper in a tree, and they caught him incidentally.
But it shattered all the bone in my nose and broke two pieces off of this bone here and
broke this bone right here, broke this bone across here, came out about here.
And when it did all this, it was so close to my eye that it detached the retina.
And that's what they had spent so much time operating on.
They tried to, they wanted to replace it if they could.
They didn't know for sure whether they could or not.
And then they had to take scrapings out of these cheekbones.
and pull it back up into the nose and squeeze it together with a little capsule of Vaseline, warm Vaseline, and hope that it grew back together.
And it did.
It did a marvelous job.
Yeah, it sure did.
And I would say that you feel that you got rid of the best of all possible medical care.
Best.
In fact, after I got out of the hospital, I was in the hospital 42 days.
They operated about 10 different times because they
A bunch of things to do.
Cut some of these bones off that were shattered.
And I had to rebuild this thing and scrape it because little, what do you call it, spurs grew on this soft bone.
And I had to cut them off every day.
Because if they get growing too much, you can't bury it, of course.
But I came out real well.
In fact, they didn't even make any plastic surgery on me.
They just replaced it and sewed it up.
Sure did.
And unless you look closely, you can't tell.
I have no difficulty breathing, a little.
This eye has about 20-90 vision.
This one has 20-40.
And I have a traumatic cataract that's been there since the day I got hit, but it hadn't grown any.
I have no cataract in this eye.
So you spent, what, 42 days?
42 days in the hospital.
That's counting the time I was on the field, too.
From the time I got wounded until I got out was 42 days.
Then what?
Excuse me.
Then what?
I rejoined the division and the Ridgeway asked me to go with him and 12 other officers to form the cadre for the 18th Airborne Corps.
The division had been pulled back to England from France after the initial stages of this thing.
I think he stayed over about 30 days because they wanted to mount this hollering operation for the airborne divisions.
So they pulled him back and they made this corps.
And I went with General Ridgway and these officers to form the bases for the 18th Airborne Corps.
The rest of the troops were brought over from the United States.
They had been the 18th Armored Division.
So we brought them over and took all of these people that came over from this armored division and tried to train them in parachute operations.
These were tankers, huh?
Yeah, these were tankers.
And this took a lot of time.
We didn't have much time to loot because this was in late July and they had this operation in Holland set up in September.
So we got the operation all set and all the planes and everything, supplies, everything ready to go.
And then General Einhard decided
that there was no particular need to send both a British and American Corps, and this particular time you're going to let the British Corps take responsibility for the operation.
So we sent two American divisions and a British division, and the British actually operated there, and they caught, well they had two up there.
We came out of it and they brought the troops back then to the area around Reims and Epperday.
Now did you go into Holland?
No, I didn't go to Holland.
I stayed in England.
And then we came from England to France in early November.
See, they mounted this operation in September.
We came in early November and moved into the Reims.
Where did you land in France?
Well, we flew from an airport in England, just plain and time, C-47, and landed in Paris, La Borgia Field.
They weren't in very good shape.
They'd already been bombed.
But we landed there and took jeeps from there up to Reims.
We set up headquarters in Reims.
Then we, from Reims in the Epernay area, we got these parachute people and glider people back from Holland.
And they lost a lot of people.
We had to resupply and put in new troops, brought in a lot of new officers
fresh from the United States, second, first lieutenant, mostly.
A lot of them were just out of West Point, brand new college graduates.
We then were called into this operation on the 19th of December, I guess.
On the 19th of December, we were just called, because we were the only troops not already committed
They just loaded us in trucks and carried us up to the Ardennes and put us out.
We had two divisions and brought another division from England across, which was the 13th Airborne.
Never been committed yet.
Anywhere, anytime.
So we slugged it out up there as ground troops, really.
And we came back to this area and moved to the Rhine River area.
where we mounted an airborne operation across the Rhine River at Zweifel.
We sent two American and one British civilians across the river by air.
And part of the unit, that is, we didn't send any gliders much or few, but part of our unit didn't go by air.
went in floats and little motorboats.
Actually, they were rafts with motors on them.
And we then transferred from there down to the central part of the country.
They got in trouble down in the river, so they sent us down into the river.
This was Bradley's order.
Converted us down there.
And we slugged it out through, all through Bonn, Dillenburg, and oh, I can't think.
I know we were in this little town.
I'm trying to think of the day we heard that Mr. Roosevelt died.
I can't even think of the name of his big cabin center there.
And then we swung around to the left, and we had this thing pretty well under control.
And they called us back to get ready to cross the Elbe River.
We crossed the Elbe River at Beckleid.
We crossed not by airborne.
We did by foot troop.
All of our paratroopers and gliders were just used as foot soldiers.
And the engineers threw up a bridge at Beckleid, and the armor division came across the next day.
We got as far as Lubbock last, which was, I guess,
we figured we'd be in Berlin in another six or seven days if they'd leave us alone.
And of course Patton was on his way there too, but the war ended.
So we just sat there.
And then soon after about
About a week after the war was over, they sent me back with a group of five to Ephrony to get ready to take all these troops back to Red Goat Pacific to get into the invasion of Japan.
I stayed with the division, with the Corps then until about the 20th of June, I guess, and they sent me with a group of 52 Texans who had been wounded two or three times.
to bring them back to the United States.
And I left there I guess about maybe the 25th of June.
We landed in New York and came on to Texas, landed in Fort Sam Houston on the 3rd of July.
I got these 52 Texans that I brought back.
But we had a whole train load of them, a whole ship load of them really that's on the ship
called Champlain, which was a World War I German plane, I mean, ship.
And we dropped off some of them in Ohio and Kentucky and all around.
There was no train coming down.
No train coming down from Fort Dix.
So then they asked me if I wanted to get out of the service or if I wanted to stay, and I was ready to get out, so I said I'm ready, and they let me out.
And I came to work in Texas, and then on the first of September,
even though I was going to terminally leave until the fourth of November.
One last wartime question.
What do you consider was the toughest combat that you went through or the hardest going in Europe?
What was the roughest time?
As far as the divisions concerned, me.
You personally.
Well, of course I thought Aside from being wounded.
Yeah, I wasn't there long enough.
I was just there about
I was just there about 30 hours before I got wounded.
No, I'd say the Ardennes Campaign was the toughest.
The cold?
I was a headquarters commandant during the Ardennes Campaign.
It was cold and the Germans had come in there with everything they had and they were scattered all over the countryside in American uniforms.
They were specially trained people and it was hard to identify them and we had to be extra cautious.
It was hard to get supplies up, and the weather was so bad we couldn't get any air support.
In fact, we were there from the afternoon of the 19th of December until the 24th before I ever saw an American bomber.
And on Christmas Eve day, we counted about a thousand American bombers that came by.
Of course, the Germans shot a lot of them down, too.
But then we lost an attack right after these bombers did their dirty work.
They hit some of these German tanks and knocked them out that we were being held up by.
So we made pretty good progress and went on up to Banau and Harzay and Frankenschamps.
And they pulled our division out if we got to Frankenschamps, which is just across the secret line.
We made pretty good progress there.
But that was the roughest.
Yes, it was the roughest.
We lost a lot of people.
It was day and night operation.
And the Germans still had some pretty good bombing support along in that area.
And they came in at low altitude.
And this was the first time we ever saw any jets, incidentally.
They sent in these jets at low altitude.
You mean 262.
Yeah.
They come scooting over those hills and drop right down on top of you.
Drop a few bombs and you never get a chance to see them, really.
And we lost a lot of people, mostly by getting minor wounds and freezing to death going into the shop.
We lost lots of guys.
Do you think maybe that the American Army was not prepared for that winter campaign?
No, I think we were pretty well prepared.
We were actually better prepared than the Germans.
I'm talking about clothing-wise?
Oh, yes.
Yeah, we ran short on some clothing, those shoe packs, for instance.
I'm just wondering if most American soldiers really had been trained, though, for extreme winter warfare.
Not if they had.
I know I was confused about it, and I was supposed to be smarter than they were, because I was older.
Well, maybe if you'd been from Minnesota, you would have known.
Yeah.
We had a lot of guys from the North, incidentally, in our division.
That should have been help.
No, I learned right away not to ever take my clothes off, except often enough to change my socks and get my feet tied.
My dad was a medical officer, and he said that the foot problems were the worst in the Ardennes.
Yeah, lots of guys with feet and ears broke.
I found lots of guys laying out there that didn't have anything to wear but a bullet hole through the shoulder.
That's all.
Now, there wouldn't be enough to kill a guy unless he'd bleed to death, but he was just stiff as a poker because he broke and went in shock, I guess.
We found others that were cut half in two and picked up by the aid men and carried back and patched up in pretty good shape.
Medical services were outstanding.
This hospital that I was in, boy, they operated on guys up there that I didn't see how they could operate.
Cut all the pieces, shell fragments, had feet blown off by those damn shoe mines, bayoneted by the Krauts, head patching, guts up.
sew them together and put them out there in pretty good shape.
Let's go on to the A&M stuff now.
You came to A&M in September of 46?
September of 45.
As Veterans Advisor.
How did you wind up getting this job?
Well, I had applied for a job with the Veterans Administration.
on the advice of a counselor in Fort Sam Houston Separation Center.
They had a veteran administration man there, and they wanted a college graduate who had taught school and been in service to work with them in their counseling program in Waco.
And I had applied, but they couldn't give me a decision until my term of leave was up, which was the 4th of November.
And about the 20th of August,
a man named Heaton, who was registrar, called me.
And I never heard of him before, but he called me and said, I got your name from E.E.
McQuillan, who is director of the Former Student Association.
And we're looking for a man, and Mr. Gilchrist told me to find somebody if I could.
And he wants a man that's an A&M graduate, preferably.
One that's been in the Army.
One that's been a schoolteacher.
or taught school somewhere.
And he said, he called me on Saturday afternoon and said, I'd like to talk to you.
And I said, well, when?
What do you want me to do?
He said, won't you be a veteran's advisor?
But he didn't know what that meant.

So I came down on Sunday afternoon, right after I got out of church, Sunday, I came with my wife and we talked to the brand new dean of men who had just reported, had gotten out of the Army at Fort Hood, came down here to be dean of men.
He can talk to me about it now.
Who was Dean of Men at this time?
Rollins.
Joe Rollins?
Joe Rollins.
J.W.
Joe Rollins.
And they told me everything they knew about the job.
Said, Mr. Gilchrist wanted me to come here and help the veterans.
That's really what he meant.
I said, well, help them do what?
He said, get in school, get the money, find a place to live, get some recreation for the families, a place for the kids to live.
And help them with the GI Bill.
if I got any hospitalization problems, disability cases, or insurance problems.
I want you to know, we want you to know everything about the GI Bill.
So I said, okay, when do you want me to go to work?
I didn't really want to go to work first September because I was tired.
I hadn't gotten completely over my last campaign.
And incidentally, that last campaign wasn't easy.
Up into the, across the Elk River.
Because we captured over,
a million prisoners, and we liberated over two million concentration camp prisoners in our core area alone.
And I was responsible for feeding these people and taking care of them the best we could.
Until the relocation people.
That's right.
Initially.
So anyhow, I went to the Veterans Administration headquarters in Waco and spent
A day in the insurance division, a day in the education division, a day in the loan division.
I learned all I could about D.W.
I came here on the first day of September.
I went to work, and in the meantime, I talked to the president, and he told me what he'd like for me to do, as best he knew.
Who was the president?
Mr. Gibb Gilchrist.
Okay.
I may ask you in a minute what your impression of him was.
Go on.
So I went to work, and they wanted me to live on campus so I'd be accessible to the students.
They had an old house down there, and I called my wife on the telephone, told her to come home and get the stuff out of the storage.
We had the storage in Waco during the war.
And she brought it down, and we opened up a house down there on, right where the new athletic dormitory is.
It was old Clark Street then.
I guess it still is.
had a little house there, and we lived in it.
Then we moved down here to the one back of Grand Hall, which was the Williams house.
There's none here anymore, but I was a, I was a vintage writer.

We had 900 students, about 900 out of GI Bill, and they were, most of them knew a little bit about it, not much, but I set up an office in the registrar's office because they didn't have any other place for me.
And there was a room about to,
20 by 20, and I would see these veterans about 20 at a time, had 20 chariots in there, and I'd see them, tell them all I knew about the G.I.
Bill, and then hand them a form and tell them, fill them out and let me see them, because I wanted them correctly filled out before we sent them in.
And I told them what their rights and privileges were and what they'd get and what school would do, and Mr. Gilchrist had raised for
a little loan fund so these guys that got out of the service without any money wouldn't have to wait, because we knew it might be 30 to 90 days before these guys got paid.
And as it turned out, this was about right.
So anyhow, we got along pretty good there.
And about the time I was getting cleared up a little bit, a new semester started in October, and we got in a whole raft of guys.
Remember how many?
About 2,000.
new fittings.
And then in February, we jumped up to about 6,000.
And one girl and I were trying to see them and tell them what they had to do.
We remember we grabbed some poop sheets and said, this covers part of it, but I'll have to explain part of it.
So I found a room where I could get, instead of 20 at the time, I got about 50, 75 in.
And had a place for them to ride.
And then when they'd fill all these things out, this girl and I would check them at night and see if they were completely accurate and then mail them in that same night so they'd get them in Waco.
And incidentally, the veterinary administration had a man, a full-time man here on the campus too, helping me with some of these problems.
I didn't know that.
Mostly, he was helping mostly disabled cases.
Can you remember what his name was?
Oh, yeah, he died about a year ago.
I'll check that for you.
Go ahead.
No, I can't remember.
Anyhow, we gave him an office over there in Hart Hall, a pair of those rooms that joined.
And he, see, at that time, we were issuing books and supplies and everything, too, and he helped me with some of the minute details.
Gee, that feels a little different then than it is now.
Yes, quite a bit.
So then I had to go out, after I got all that done, I had to see if I could find someplace, and we did.
We set up, with permission and help of the dining hall people, Jay Penderson was in charge of the dining hall at Speedy Hall.
We set up a portion of that second floor there as a sort of a lounge, recreation, education area for the families of these veterans.
We had converted Walton Hall
and Hart Hall into apartments.
And we took two other dormitories down there and just let a man and his wife live in a room.
Now, let me get this again.
I wasn't aware of that.
Hart Hall was in Walton.
Hart Hall.
We took two rooms.
You see those rooms in Hart?
They have a bathroom in between.
They used to live in them.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Well, then we made an apartment out of that.
Now, what year was this?
19... Well, we started this operation.
It took us about a year to get it all done.
We started this operation shortly after I came here.
Mr. Spence and Calvin Moore.
And I collaborated with Mr. Gilchrist on this and we got these things all converted and put in a little stove and a little refrigerator and still use the bunk beds.
Yeah.
And had a desk for the guy.
So they had really kind of a living room kitchen affair and then a bedroom on the other side.
That's what he meant to.
How long did that go on?
That went on about two years and then we got
We, incidentally, we started working right away to get some of those old trailers, what they call mobile homes that the Air Force people used to use.
We put some of them right down there where Coliseum is now.
Then on down toward the south, right next to the American Legion House on both sides of the street, we put those prefabs in.
We had about 200 of those.
Now we took, we got about 12, 13 of those old Navy houses from Orange, Texas.
Where'd you get the College View?
We got them from Air Force Base down there.
Victoria?
Victoria.
Foster Field.
Foster?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
And they moved them up here and installed them with whatever pipes and fixes they could get, and we started renting them as fast as we could.
And you began to clear the people out.
We began to need them for single people.
We didn't need them because we had three men in all the rooms.
This wasn't good, because they're not built for three.
But we set up this place, and we got somebody, and I don't even remember now, I think, the extension service managed to get some sewing machines.
And they had classes for these wives to teach them how to sew and how to pick out curtain materials and how to cook and cut meat and buy meat and stuff like that.
They had a few pool tables and a few ping pong tables.
put down in that old dining hall, second floor there.
And we built little drying yards in the back of the apartments where the kids' diapers could be dried and stuff like that.
What were your major problems now during this, other than innovating a program that had never been tried before?
Do you think there were any major problems that you had?
Yes, there were some problems because... That you can't talk about?
A good many of these people were more crowded in, even though they'd been crowded up during the war, they were crowded in in short quarters.
And those people that lived off the campus, remember now, we had 6,000 people here, and a high percentage of these people were married, had a wife at least, and most of them had children.
When they moved off the campus, they lived in chicken coops and every kind of thing.
They didn't like this, and they weren't happy.
And we were, too, because a lot of them weren't even sanitary.
And we had to fight their battles, incidentally, with the rent control people, because they were making these guys pay under the table.
They'd come tell me, and I'd have to go to the rent control people and say, I know this is a fact, and I'm willing to go to court and testify.
I see.
Because we felt like we ought to represent these kids.
These were men, really.
And some of the wives were unhappy because they didn't have any recreational facilities.
See, we didn't even let them go swimming at the swimming pool and stuff like that.
The only thing we had was an old campus picture show at Guyon Hall.
And we didn't even have, we had three bowling alleys, one under four in a YMCA base.
And this is not many.
We had a few ping pong tables.
So they didn't have any place for recreation and entertainment.
And the university hadn't decided for sure who could go to football games.
And all these guys weren't carrying their wires, of course, and stuff like that.
They finally did, but we had to go represent them, and we want these Y's in at the same rate the students get in, because these guys can't afford commercial rates.
And they got so many people going to basketball games, and we alternated.
Up to a certain letter would go one time, and the next time the other group would go, so you couldn't see but half the ball games.
And they were better pleased, and those that didn't,
have places to cook, to go in the dining hall and eat, which was new.
We never had let this happen before.
And some of the ladies wanted to go to school then.
And they still had a policy against ladies going to school except in summertime.
They'd let them go in summer, but they would let them go in the fall and spring.
Couldn't go to the college hospital.
And this was a problem because with 6,000 new families in town,
The medical staff here in Brown couldn't take care of them.
And there was no real system for hiring these girls to work at that time.
And incidentally, this girl who worked for me, whose husband was a student, incidentally, she had a master's degree from Rice.
But her husband was tech and civil engineering and was a bomber pilot.
And she knew about all this stuff.
So she and I organized it first.
program for helping these girls find jobs.
So if a veteran's wife, and we specified a veteran's wife because we're not supposed to be the rest of them married.
So they'd come and ask me if I knew where to get a job.
Well, I contacted all the officers on the campus and told them we had a veteran.
She said, please let me know.
And we hired lots of girls through our office, this little girl and I.
All we'd do is find out where the jobs were and send them to them.
So this was kind of a placement office on the side then?
Sort of, yeah.
Any student that didn't have enough money come in and say, sir, I got a grocery bill.
I got a child in the hospital.
What can I do?
Well, so I'd go to Mr. Gilchrist again and say, Mr. Gilchrist, these guys don't have enough money to do this.
So he set aside a certain amount of money in the fiscal office.
I don't know where he got the money.
I guess it was out of one of these slush funds they had.
And he told me that we could loan up to $100
for 90 days, for instance.
So I just had a guy sign a bill for them.
I promised to pay within 90 days.
No interest.
And we collected most of it.
We didn't lose very much.
We didn't lose much.
We didn't lose many of them.
What do you think of the veterans as a whole coming back?
You think they were pretty good students as a whole?
Those students, yeah.
That was the best thing that ever happened with Texas A&M, in my opinion, because they raised the scholastic standards.
And I know this because of cadets as a whole.
They didn't want those veterans over here because, first place, they weren't in uniform.
Then many didn't go back into the Corps when they came back?
Not very many went back in.
Few.
A few.
Not very many.
You see, you got to remember, too, that a hell of a lot of these guys were officers already.
And a lot of them majors and lieutenant colonels.
One hell of a lot of lieutenants and captains, but there were a lot of majors and lieutenant colonels.
And a few chicken colonels.
I thought maybe you might have a few of the enlisted types that came back and wanted a commission.
They were.
They were.
And I remember the 1st Sergeant of F Company.
I remember the 1st Sergeant of B Company.
They were enlisted men.
One of them was a Marine incidentally.
And they got commissions.
We had one company of nothing but veterans.
One full company.
Everybody in there was a veteran.
And they did a real good job.
They didn't try to throw their weight around or anything.
In other words, you don't think that the veterans coming back were not any rougher than those that were here then?
No.
Those, in fact, they were better.
In fact, a lot of the things that we found out were going on in the corps that we didn't like, information was given to us by veterans.
A lot of them were ex-Aggies, incidentally, that had been here before the war and came back.
I said, they're running it.
They're brutalizing the thing.
Now, we don't want our name mentioned, please.
I said, no, anything you tell me, then go beyond.
I never even told Mr. Gilkish where I got my information.
Then some of the hazing that went on was really not caused by the veterans coming back.
No.
No, most of it was caused by the new students coming in.
That's right.
That's something I didn't know.
Yeah.
When I went to work at A&M, they were about
I don't remember exactly now, but there was approximately 1,900 freshman cadets and about 100 upperclassmen cadets.
Now, a lot of these upperclassmen were veterinarians who had been exempt, see, on account of the practice that they were getting into.
And a few of these guys were veterans who had come back.
I remember one guy that had a whole hand shot off, and they let him be a cadet.
And he was a junior.
He didn't cause any trouble, but all these sophomores were the ones he caused trouble.
And there weren't very many of them.
But they were not veterans.
No, they were flailing and living there outside of those poor freshmen.
Is this the time that they moved the freshmen to?
Well, they did that later.
I don't remember because, see, they were still operating the base out there.
And I think it was about 19-
I think it was about 1948 or 49 that they opened that base out there for those freshmen.

I'm not sure about that date, but it was, I know I served, I served, well, let me go on and get this thing, this date thing may fall into place here, but I, no, I thought the veterans on the whole, now they were, they caused some problems because they, for instance, they had what they called a revolt meeting over there one night, and
I went to the president of this Veterans Association and told him that I was working for the university and I'm the veterans advisor and I want to know what you all are going to do.
He said, it's not any of your business.
I said, it sure is.
Anything you do on this campus is none of my business.
Now I want to know what you're going to discuss.
So he said, we're going to protest.
What are you going to protest?
So I said, I'm coming.
I'm coming to the meeting.
And I was.
I went over and sat on the front row where he couldn't miss seeing me.

I said, I'll take them one by one in order that they were introduced here.
You people voted on these things.
You want to delete English.
A&M couldn't delete English if they wanted to.
They wouldn't want to in the first place, but they couldn't if they wanted to because the Southern Association would bar us.
They'd discredit us completely.
Now, it's just that simple.
Now, A&M's not going to eliminate English 101 and 102.

Now, you talked about, you talked about
you know, we want two guys in the room.

There's no other place to go.
And if we're going to have two in a room, that's a third of all the guys here got to leave.
Now which third wants to go?
So they hadn't thought about that.
So then,
Some guy up in the balcony, he jumped up, and he had his wife with him.
And he said, I think we ought to reconsider everything we voted on, because I didn't think about that.
I'm glad Mr. Zinn came here, and I didn't think about that.

We have to know how many.
And if we don't, and half of you don't go, we've got to go up on the food prices.
We've got to double it.
And this is prohibitive to a lot of people.

And I don't want to talk to him about all these things.
And we're not being arbitrary about it.
And I'm not talking about what was then.
I'm talking about the university now.
We've got to try to run a sensible educational institution.
